li.p:
We find the characteristic polynomial of A to be
\det(A-\lambda I) = \lambda^2-\frac52\lambda+\frac12 p\text{,}
which has roots \lambda=\frac 54 \pm \frac12\sqrt{\frac94-2p}\text{.}
So long as \frac94 - 2p\geq 0, one root will be real and larger than 1. We have a saddle when
\begin{aligned} \frac 54 - \frac12\sqrt{\frac94-2p} \amp \lt 1 \\ \sqrt{\frac94-2p} \amp \gt \frac12 \\ p \amp \lt 1\text{.} \\ \end{aligned}
This shows that we have a saddle whenever p\lt1.

statement.p:
The Fibonacci numbers form the sequence of numbers that begins 0, 1, 1, 2, 3, 5, 8, 13, \ldots. If we let F_n denote the n^{th} Fibonacci number, then
F_0 =0, F_1 =1, F_2 =1, F_3 =2, F_4 =3,\ldots . In general, a Fibonacci number is the sum of the previous two Fibonacci numbers; that is, F_{n+2} = F_{n}+F_{n+1} so that we have
\begin{aligned} F_{n+2} \amp {}={} F_{n} + F_{n+1} \\ F_{n+1} \amp {}={} F_{n+1}\text{.} \\ \end{aligned}

li.p:
Show that A has eigenvalues
\begin{aligned} \lambda_1 \amp {}={} \frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2}\approx 1.61803\ldots \\ \lambda_2 \amp {}={} \frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2}\approx -0.61803\ldots \\ \end{aligned}
with associated eigenvectors \vvec_1=\twovec{\lambda_1}{1} and \vvec_2=\twovec{\lambda_2}{1}.

 We have
	\xvec_{n+1}=\twovec{F_{n+2}}{F_{n+1}} =
	\twovec{F_{n+1}+F_n}{F_{n+1}}
	= \left[\begin{array}{rr}
	1 \amp 1 \\
	1 \amp 0 \\
	\end{array}\right]
	\xvec_n\text{.}

The characteristic equation is
\det(A-\lambda I) = (1-\lambda)(-\lambda)-1 = \lambda^2-\lambda-1 = 0\text{.}
Applying the quadratic formula, we see that the two eigenvalues are \lambda_1=\frac{1+\sqrt5}{2} and \lambda_2=\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}2.
